                        <handDesc>
                          <handNote script="Ethiopic" xml:id="h1">
                            <seg type="ink">Black, red</seg>
                          </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <decoDesc>
                          <decoNote type="drawing" xml:id="d5">
                          <desc>Pencil drawing on the left pastedown, depicting a geometrical pattern.</desc>
                          </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="band" xml:id="d1">
                              <locus target="#1ra">Fol. 1ra</locus>
                              <desc>Simple ornamental band at the incipit of the text, added later in black ink.</desc>
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="drawing" xml:id="d2">
                              <locus target="#1r #19v">Fols. 1r, 19v</locus>
                              <desc>Pencil drawing in the lower margin, depicting an animal, perhaps a horse.</desc>
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="band" xml:id="d3">
                              <locus target="#26va #30vb #59rb">Fols. 26va, 30vb, 59rb</locus>
                              <desc>Simple ornamental band: two rows of black and red dots with three punctuation marks in between.</desc>
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="punctuation" xml:id="d4">
                              <locus target="#48va #63vb">Fols. 48va, 63vb</locus>
                              <desc>Row of black and red dots.</desc>
                            </decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
<additions><list><item xml:id="a1"><locus from="64r" to="64v">Fols 64r–64v</locus><desc type="GuestText">Liturgical text</desc></item></list></additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                          <binding contemporary="partly" xml:id="binding">
                            <decoNote xml:id="b1">
                              Ethiopic bookbinding with plain wooden boards preserved in its slip case.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="bindingMaterial">
                           <material key="wood"/>
                           <material key="paper"/>
                        </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Boards">
                              The boards, smaller than the bookblock, could have been reused from another codex.
                              The inner surface of the boards is plain and well smoothed while on the outer side the signs of the tool are visible.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="SewingStations">4</decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b7">
                              The sewing is a chain-stitch on four sewing stations (two pairs). The sewing is a variation of <term key="patternA" ana="#patternA">pattern A</term> defined by G. Bozzacchi.
                              For each sewing station a thread of <term key="animalThread" ana="#animalThread">animal origin</term> has been used. Two ends of the thread are knotted along the centrefold of the first quire,
                              the other two pass each other and continue the sewing.
                              The sewing is closed in the last quire, knotting the threads together after they entered in the boards.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b9" type="Spine">
                              Small holes are present close to the head and tail of the quires, probably remains of the tackets.
                              Quires 1, 10 and 11 have additional holes, perhaps traces of a previous sewing or errors occurred during the preparation of the quires.</decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b11" type="EndLeaves" pastedown="L OTI">
                              The inner surface of the front board is covered with paper. Traces of paper are found also on the external surface.</decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b12" type="SlipCase">
                              The book is kept inside its two-parts slip case, made of stiff leather.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b13" type="other">
                              Various red threads are sewn into the corners of <locus target="#1r #30r #48r #50r">folss. 1r, 30r, 48r, 50r, </locus> while on fols. <locus target="#26 #56 #59">26, 56, 59</locus> just the holes are left.
                              A white thread is looped around the first chain-stitch on the spine and used as bookmark.</decoNote>
                          </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                      </physDesc>

